The paper introduces a new transactional filesystem that is POSIX-compatible and enables efficient file transformations. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Distributed Systems (cs.DS) sub-category, as it deals with a distributed filesystem. Additionally, the paper discusses the performance of the new filesystem compared to the industry-standard HDFS distributed filesystem, which further supports the likelihood of it belonging to the Distributed Systems sub-category. The paper also mentions the file slicing API, which could potentially fall under the Database (cs.DB) sub-category. The paper's focus on high-performance applications suggests that it could also belong to the Distributed Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. Finally, the paper's discussion of microbenchmarks and the POSIX-compatible API suggests that it could belong to the Operating Systems (cs.OS) sub-category.
